New York 2020
nytimes_articles.abstract:
It is the year 2020 and residents of the once vibrant New York region are stuck in apartments they cannot unload in crumbling urban centers. Suburbanites  are faring no better. This is one bleak scenario presented in "A Region at Risk," a five-year study by the Regional Plan Association. 

     This picture cannot be dismissed: Too many of the region's core industries lost ground between 1982 and 1992. But there is far more reason to believe, as the association does, that long-term planning and a relatively modest investment will enable the region to retain its status as the global capital.

wiki_events.headline: In Philadelphia, world champion Garry Kasparov beats the Deep Blue supercomputer in a chess match.

pages.title: Philadelphia
pages.description: Most populous city in Pennsylvania, US
pages.abstract: Philadelphia, colloquially referred to as Philly, is the most populous city in the U.S. state of Pennsylvania. It is the sixth-most populous city in the United States with a population of 1.6 million at the 2020 census, while the Philadelphia metropolitan area with 6.33 million residents is the nation's ninth-largest metropolitan area. Philadelphia is known for its culture, cuisine, and history, maintaining contemporary influence in business and technology, sports, and music.

pages.title: Garry Kasparov
pages.abstract: Garry Kimovich Kasparov is a Russian chess grandmaster, political activist and writer, who was the World Chess Champion from 1985 to 2000. His peak FIDE chess rating of 2851, achieved in 1999, was the highest recorded until being surpassed by Magnus Carlsen in 2013. From 1984 until his retirement from regular competitive chess in 2005, Kasparov was ranked the world's No. 1 player for a record 255 months overall. Kasparov also holds records for the most consecutive professional tournament victories (15) and Chess Oscars (11).

pages.title: Deep Blue (chess computer)
pages.abstract: Deep Blue was a customized IBM RS/6000 SP supercomputer for chess-playing designed by computer scientist Feng-hsiung Hsu. It was the first computer to win a game, and the first to win a match, against a reigning world champion under regular time controls. Development began in 1985 at Carnegie Mellon University under the name ChipTest. It then moved to IBM, where it was first renamed Deep Thought, then again in 1989 to Deep Blue. In 1996, it was used to compete against world champion Garry Kasparov in a six-game match, where it won one, drew two, and lost three games. In 1997, it underwent an upgrade, and in a six-game rematch it defeated Kasparov by winning two games and drawing three. Deep Blue's victory is considered a milestone in the history of artificial intelligence and has been the subject of several books and films.

pages.title: Supercomputer
pages.abstract: A supercomputer is a type of computer with a high level of performance as compared to a general-purpose computer. Supercomputers play an important role in the field of computational science, and are used for a wide range of computationally intensive tasks in various fields including quantum mechanics, weather forecasting, climate research, oil and gas exploration, molecular modeling, and physical simulations. They have been essential in the field of cryptanalysis.

pages.title: Chess
pages.description: Traditional board game for two players
pages.abstract: Chess is a board game for two players, played on a square board consisting of 64 squares arranged in an 8Ã—8 grid. The players, referred to as "White" and "Black", each control sixteen pieces: one king, one queen, two rooks, two bishops, two knights, and eight pawns, with each piece type having a different pattern of movement. An enemy piece may be captured by moving one's own piece onto the square it occupies. The object of the game is to "checkmate" the enemy king. There are also several ways a game can end in a draw.

wiki_events.headline: NASA's Discovery Program begins as the NEAR Shoemaker spacecraft lifts off on the first mission ever to orbit and land on an asteroid, 433 Eros.

pages.title: NASA
pages.abstract: The National Aeronautics and Space Administration is an independent agency of the U.S. federal government responsible for the United States' civil space program and for research in aeronautics and space exploration. Headquartered in Washington, D.C., NASA operates ten field centers across the United States and is organized into mission directorates for Science, Space Operations, Exploration Systems Development, Space Technology, Aeronautics Research, and Mission Support. Established in 1958, NASA succeeded the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (NACA) to give the American space development effort a distinct civilian orientation, emphasizing peaceful applications in space science. It has since led most of America's space exploration programs, including Project Mercury, Project Gemini, the 1968â€“1972 Apollo program missions, the Skylab space station, and the Space Shuttle.

pages.title: Discovery Program
pages.description: Solar system exploration program by NASA
pages.abstract: The Discovery Program is a series of Solar System exploration missions funded by the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) through its Planetary Missions Program Office. The cost of each mission is capped at a lower level than missions from NASA's New Frontiers or Flagship Programs. As a result, Discovery missions tend to be more focused on a specific scientific goal rather than serving a general purpose.

pages.title: NEAR Shoemaker
pages.abstract: Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous â€“ Shoemaker, renamed after its 1996 launch in honor of planetary scientist Eugene Shoemaker, was a robotic space probe designed by the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory for NASA to study the near-Earth asteroid Eros from close orbit over a period of a year. It was the first spacecraft to orbit an asteroid and land on it successfully. In February 2000, the mission closed in on the asteroid and orbited it. On February 12, 2001, Shoemaker touched down on the asteroid and was terminated just over two weeks later.

pages.title: 433 Eros
pages.abstract: 433 Eros is a stony asteroid of the Amor group, and the first discovered, and second-largest near-Earth object. It has an elongated shape and a volume-equivalent diameter of approximately 16.8 kilometers.

wiki_events.headline: The 8.2 Mwâ€¯ Biak earthquake shakes the Papua province of eastern Indonesia with a maximum Mercalli intensity of VIII (Severe). A large tsunami followed, leaving 166 people dead or missing and 423 injured.

pages.title: 1996 Biak earthquake
pages.description: Earthquake and tsunami in eastern Indonesia
pages.abstract: The 1996 Biak earthquake, or the Irian Jaya earthquake, occurred on 17 February at 14:59:30 local time near Biak Island, Indonesia. The earthquake, which occurred on the New Guinea Trench, had a moment magnitude of 8.2 and a maximum Mercalli intensity of IX (Violent). The run-up height of the generated tsunami reached 7.7Â m (25Â ft). The disaster left at least 108 people dead, 423 injured, and 58 missing. It damaged or destroyed 5,043 houses which subsequently made another 10,000 homeless. At Korim, 187 houses were destroyed. Various countries and organizations provided aid and relief in the aftermath of the earthquake.

pages.title: Papua (province)
pages.description: Province in Western New Guinea, Indonesia
pages.abstract: Papua, formerly known as West Irian and Irian Jaya, is a province of Indonesia, comprising the northern coast of Western New Guinea together with island groups in Cenderawasih Bay to the west. It roughly follows the borders of the Papuan customary region of Mamta â€“ Saireri and is divided into eight regencies and one city (kota), the latter being the provincial capital of Jayapura.

pages.title: Indonesia
pages.description: Country in Southeast Asia and Oceania
pages.abstract: Indonesia, officially the Republic of Indonesia, is a country in Southeast Asia and Oceania, between the Indian and Pacific oceans. Comprising over 17,000 islands, including Sumatra, Java, Sulawesi, and parts of Borneo and New Guinea, Indonesia is the world's largest archipelagic state and the 14th-largest country by area, at 1,904,569 square kilometres. Indonesia has significant areas of wilderness that support one of the world's highest levels of biodiversity. It shares land borders with Papua New Guinea, Timor-Leste, and Malaysia, as well as maritime borders with seven other countries, including Australia, Singapore, and the Philippines.

pages.title: Modified Mercalli intensity scale
pages.description: Seismic intensity scale used to quantify the degree of shaking during earthquakes
pages.abstract: The Modified Mercalli intensity scale measures the effects of an earthquake at a given location. This is in contrast with the seismic magnitude usually reported for an earthquake.

nytimes_articles.abstract:
When Emory Campbell moved a few collapsed cabinets in the flooded garage of his neighbor Josephine Galvani in the aftermath of the great flood of Jan. 19, he noticed an unusual agitation in a pool of standing water. Looking closely, he discovered a small trout. The fish had apparently been swept from the nearby upper Beaverkill River into the garage at the peak of the flood and left stranded when the water finally receded. 

     "I asked Josephine for a glass," Campbell said recently, "and I put the trout into it with some water. Then I went down to the river and poured out the little fish. It took right off, so I assume the fish was O.K."

nytimes_articles.abstract:
GROWING up in Linden, my brother and I played at opposite ends of 18th Street. The street was three blocks long, bordered on the east by Rosenbaum's Dairy Farm and on the west by a small airport. The dairy farm no longer exists.  The airport prospered, along with the vision that held my brother captive for 50 years. 

     Each spring, the pungent smell of manure and the sweet damp smell of new earth lured me to Rosenbaum's fields and barn doors. Hens strutted and pecked; ducks waddled near a marshy pond; seven complacent cows chewed and stared at me.

A Game We Couldn't Lose
nytimes_articles.abstract:
Human worth hung in the balance again this weekend. Among the array of graver and more material contests now facing civilization, struggles from Sarajevo to New Hampshire, the one decided yesterday in Philadelphia stands out in its symbolic weight. In the chess match between Garry Kasparov, the world's best living player, and I.B.M.'s Deep Blue, an otherwise undistinguished supercomputer, humanity's collective self-esteem was once more on the line. 

     The latest blow to our chauvinism began in the first round of the six-game match when Deep Blue bested our best after only 36 moves. Although Mr. Kasparov  rallied to avoid humiliation in the series, the early result shocked not only the chess world; it shattered the pride of those of us who would never dream of  pitting our own worth against a $15 home computer program. Suddenly, we once again needed to explain ourselves to ourselves.

Books in Brief: FICTION & POETRY;A WASP's Tale
nytimes_articles.abstract: Louis Auchincloss has modeled his latest novel on the 1918 American classic "The Education of Henry Adams," whose author a friend once called "the only man  in the world who could sit on a fence and watch himself go by." Writing in 1975  at the age of 80, the narrator of THE EDUCATION OF OSCAR FAIRFAX (Houghton Mifflin, $22.95) describes his own coming of age with the same ironic detachment. With one grandfather the Episcopal Bishop of New York and the other the founder of an eminent Wall Street law firm, Oscar receives an education that is less sentimental than perfectly decorous, its lessons encouraging Social Register virtues: tact, compromise, genteel humility, excellent manners. After Yale and Columbia Law School, he abandons his dreams of a literary career to join the family legal practice, following his father's advice that it provides the best arena for his "constant preoccupation," people  watching. ("He said it didn't matter in which I took the greater interest: the clients or the law.") And there are plenty of opportunities for social observation: a Supreme Court Justice whose opinions on torts and contracts "read like short stories by Henry James"; a gossipy Hungarian princess who hobnobbed with Proust; a talented bounder who wins a partnership in the Fairfax law firm,  marriage to Oscar's sister and national prominence in World War II. There is even a cameo appearance by Edith Wharton, Mr. Auchincloss's literary progenitor, showing off the roses in her garden in France. More a series of vignettes than a novel, the book has a few weak spots: the dialogue can be too starched and frilly, and a Spanish daughter-in-law seems to exist only so that Oscar can deliver opinions on Franco. Yet Mr. Auchincloss's own voice remains a seductive  one -- crisp, stately and wonderfully controlled.   Donna Rifkind

A scrambly, international marathon of early-1900 autos, it carries the likes of Tony Curtis, Natalie Wood, Dorothy Provine and Peter Falk, under Balke Edwards's blithe direction. The show-stealer is a sneering, villainous Jack Lemmon (above with Mr. Falk). Expect a few lulls but not many -- WEDNESDAY at 1:15 P.M. on AMC. For the record, a song called "The Sweetheart Tree" copped an Oscar as the year's best and then disappeared.

Israel's Second City
nytimes_articles.abstract:
TOURS of Israel usually give Tel Aviv short shrift. A few days at the beginning or the end and that's that. This was my third tour over a period of 20 years, and it was still Jerusalem the Golden that got most of the attention and  almost all the respect. In Jerusalem malls at night, even carousing kids wear yarmulkes, and people on the street stare at you if you're a grown woman walking around in pants. Compared with all this piety, the mood in Tel Aviv is stunningly secular. In this city, which variously calls itself the Big Orange, the City That Never Stops, and the City That Never Takes a Break (who writes their p.r., I wonder?), it's hard to imagine anyone looking at you askance about anything. This is the contemporary version of the vision that Theodor Herzl, the founder of Zionism, had of a cosmopolitan city on the sea: Tel Aviv -- literally a hill (man-made) of spring (new life). Where once there was absolutely nothing, there is now an urban sprawl of about 350,000 people -- nearly two million if you count suburbs -- and a lot of awful architecture that springs up from a flat terrain with nowhere to hide. I suppose that depending on whether you come here  first or last on a trip to Israel, you say, "Look what they've accomplished," or "My God,what have they done?" 

      Still, once you've said one or the other, and if you let it, Tel Aviv is a place that grows on you -- because it really is teeming with life, at all hours  and especially at night, a combination Oriental bazaar and Miami Beach, with the Mediterranean grace notes of Nice thrown in. Since its long Mediterranean coast  is a major asset, Tel Aviv could be taken simply as a beach resort and left at that. The rest of Israel boasts of making the land green. Tel Aviv seems to have done the opposite. Hotel follows hotel along the shore, blocking views of the water with entrances on Hayarkon Street, one of the main arteries of the city. Where you stay probably determines what you feel about the beach. The view from my balcony in the Moriah Plaza, a big and busy hotel, strongly suggested Miami. A terrace at the super luxe Dan Tel Aviv, only a few blocks to the south, seemed to look out on a resplendent Cote d'Azur.

Under the Smoky Skies of Bamako
nytimes_articles.abstract:
THERE are bats in the trees of Bamako, Mali. If you are not looking for them, you probably will not notice them, at least not from street level. But they're up there all right, in the trees, hanging in clusters, their squirming not easily noticeable against the movement of the leaves. 

     As you walk the streets of Bamako you do not think about the bats overhead --there is too much going on around you. Most of the streets are of a powdery red sand and without sidewalks so that there is a casual commingling of vehicles and pedestrians. Here and there you can see small patches of macadam -- many of  these streets were paved back when the city had more money. The only useful sidewalks run along the several broad boulevards that cross the city at seemingly random angles.

nytimes_articles.headline: Winter Break, and the Schedule Is Full
nytimes_articles.abstract:
THE sound of school doors closing for winter break need not be an ominous one for parents wondering how to fill the many hours of free time their children will be granted this week. 

     Winter break is always a great time to do more of what is always available. Time-honored recreations like sledding, ice skating, skiing or staying warm inside with a book plucked from the shelf of the local library are always available. Snow angels aside, there are plenty of opportunities this week for youngsters to engage in activities that can introduce them to new pursuits (often with the whole family), nurture an appreciation for nature or simply provide the fun they clamor for at break time. Some events promise a few hours of enjoyment, and some are weeklong camp programs.

VIEWPOINT: MARK R. MITCHELL;Stumbling Back Into Vietnam
nytimes_articles.abstract:
IN offices throughout Ho Chi Minh City and in the grimy bars where prematurely grizzled expatriates exchange gossip, the consensus is that America  is sinking into yet another quagmire in Vietnam. Unlike savvy old-timers from Asia and Europe, newly arrived American businessmen are venturing into a murky business world without the knowledge or adaptability to compete. 

     It should not be surprising that Americans are again swarming to Vietnam. For decades, Westerners have had debilitating addictions to the country. Some have been hooked by its exotic, back-alley opium dens; others, like the American military, have had fixations on its prime geopolitical real estate.

Life at the Top in Costa Rica
nytimes_articles.abstract:
IN the cool dawn light, I was hurriedly packing, tucking mosquito nets and flashlights into our duffel bags. My husband, our 6-year-old son and I had awoken to a rooster crowing outside our hotel on the outskirts of San Jose, Costa Rica's capital, ready to leave room service for the rain forest. Visions of butterflies and jaguars beckoned, as we were whisked through the still deserted streets for our charter plane to Corcovado National Park, one of the largest, least accessible, and most biologically significant of any tropical forest park in Costa Rica and one of the last refuges in the world for such threatened species as the jaguar, the ocelot and the tapir. 

     An overland trip by bus, car or jeep from San Jose to Corcovado can take as long as nine hours over rough terrain, yet the park, created in 1975 to ward off the threat of increased logging and gold mining to its exotic plants and animals, still attracts a spirited caravan of backpackers and eco-tourists. The  80-minute plane ride we chose instead, part of a four-day expedition package provided by Costa Rica Expeditions, gave us spectacular views of the coast and the lowland rain forest of Corcovado, situated on the Osa Peninsula, which protrudes into the Pacific just north of Panama.

FROM THE DESK OF: LLOYD M. KRIEGER;Hey, Mac, Don't Fail Me Now!
nytimes_articles.abstract:
MEMBERS of my computer-savvy generation can be divided into two groups: PC people and Macintosh people. The difference goes beyond what sits on our desks or what we carry in our briefcases. It reflects our attitude about our work and  ourselves. 

     I have always been a Macintosh person. I got hooked while in college at Stanford, a stone's throw from Silicon Valley. I bought my first Mac when I was  a sophomore in 1986. I used it to write term papers and to make presentations and run statistics for my biology class. It was a modular design, without wires  and a separate monitor. In that pre-laptop era, on a warm day, I would take it outside and work in the sun.

nytimes_articles.abstract:
The American who wishes to cook Chinese food at home must understand what the Chinese-food scholar Barbara Tropp calls the subliminal role of yin (that which is feminine, dark and yielding) and yang (that which is masculine, bright and hard).

In "The Chinese Banquet Cookbook" and "From the Earth: Chinese Vegetarian Cooking," Eileen Yin-Fei Lo has a chatty way of putting the dishes in their context, making fun of what she refers to as all the "chop-chop-chop." 

For the novice who wishes to cook Chinese food on a cold day, when the body yearns for a little cultural exchange, Lo has a sensible suggestion, and one that couldn't be more fashionable. Ergo, make soup.
